{"id": "17944", "revid": "27015025", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=17944", "title": "Lie algebra", "text": "Algebraic structure used in analysis\nIn mathematics, a Lie algebra (pronounced ) is a vector space formula_1 together with an operation called the Lie bracket, an alternating bilinear map formula_2, that satisfies the Jacobi identity. In other words, a Lie algebra is an algebra over a field for which the multiplication operation (called the Lie bracket) is alternating and satisfies the Jacobi identity. The Lie bracket of two vectors formula_3 and formula_4 is denoted formula_5. A Lie algebra is typically a non-associative algebra. However, every associative algebra gives rise to a Lie algebra, consisting of the same vector space with the commutator Lie bracket, formula_6.\nLie algebras are closely related to Lie groups, which are groups that are also smooth manifolds: every Lie group gives rise to a Lie algebra, which is the tangent space at the identity. (In this case, the Lie bracket measures the failure of commutativity for the Lie group.) Conversely, to any finite-dimensional Lie algebra over the real or complex numbers, there is a corresponding connected Lie group, unique up to covering spaces (Lie's third theorem). This correspondence allows one to study the structure and classification of Lie groups in terms of Lie algebras, which are simpler objects of linear algebra.\nIn more detail: for any Lie group, the multiplication operation near the identity element 1 is commutative to first order. In other words, every Lie group \"G\" is (to first order) approximately a real vector space, namely the tangent space formula_7 to \"G\" at the identity. To second order, the group operation may be non-commutative, and the second-order terms describing the non-commutativity of \"G\" near the identity give formula_7 the structure of a Lie algebra. It is a remarkable fact that these second-order terms (the Lie algebra) completely determine the group structure of \"G\" near the identity. They even determine \"G\" globally, up to covering spaces.\nIn physics, Lie groups appear as symmetry groups of physical systems, and their Lie algebras (tangent vectors near the identity) may be thought of as infinitesimal symmetry motions. Thus Lie algebras and their representations are used extensively in physics, notably in quantum mechanics and particle physics.\nAn elementary example (not directly coming from an associative algebra) is the 3-dimensional space formula_9 with Lie bracket defined by the cross product formula_10 This is skew-symmetric since formula_11, and instead of associativity it satisfies the Jacobi identity:\nformula_12\nThis is the Lie algebra of the Lie group of rotations of space, and each vector formula_13 may be pictured as an infinitesimal rotation around the axis formula_14, with angular speed equal to the magnitude\nof formula_14. The Lie bracket is a measure of the non-commutativity between two rotations. Since a rotation commutes with itself, one has the alternating property formula_16.\nA fundamental example of a Lie algebra is the space of all linear maps from a vector space to itself, as discussed below. When the vector space has dimension \"n\", this Lie algebra is called the general linear Lie algebra, formula_17. Equivalently, this is the space of all formula_18 matrices. The Lie bracket is defined to be the commutator of matrices (or linear maps), formula_19.\nHistory.\nLie algebras were introduced to study the concept of infinitesimal transformations by Sophus Lie in the 1870s, and independently discovered by Wilhelm Killing in the 1880s. The name \"Lie algebra\" was given by Hermann Weyl in the 1930s; in older texts, the term \"infinitesimal group\" was used.\nDefinition of a Lie algebra.\nA Lie algebra is a vector space formula_20 over a field formula_21 together with a binary operation formula_22 called the Lie bracket, satisfying the following axioms:\nformula_23\nformula_24\nfor all scalars formula_25 in formula_21 and all elements formula_27 in formula_7.\nformula_29\nfor all formula_3 in formula_7.\n formula_32\nfor all formula_27 in formula_7.\nGiven a Lie group, the Jacobi identity for its Lie algebra follows from the associativity of the group operation.\nUsing bilinearity to expand the Lie bracket formula_35 and using the alternating property shows that formula_36 for all formula_37 in formula_7. Thus bilinearity and the alternating property together imply\n formula_39\nfor all formula_37 in formula_7. If the field does not have characteristic 2, then anticommutativity implies the alternating property, since it implies formula_42\n formula_44\nfor all formula_27 in formula_7. \nIt is customary to denote a Lie algebra by a lower-case fraktur letter such as formula_47. If a Lie algebra is associated with a Lie group, then the algebra is denoted by the fraktur version of the group's name: for example, the Lie algebra of SU(\"n\") is formula_48.\nGenerators and dimension.\nThe \"dimension\" of a Lie algebra over a field means its dimension as a vector space. In physics, a vector space basis of the Lie algebra of a Lie group \"G\" may be called a set of \"generators\" for \"G\". (They are \"infinitesimal generators\" for \"G\", so to speak.) In mathematics, a set \"S\" of \"generators\" for a Lie algebra formula_7 means a subset of formula_7 such that any Lie subalgebra (as defined below) that contains \"S\" must be all of formula_7. Equivalently, formula_7 is spanned (as a vector space) by all iterated brackets of elements of \"S\".\nBasic examples.\nAbelian Lie algebras.\nA Lie algebra is called abelian if its Lie bracket is identically zero. Any vector space formula_53 endowed with the identically zero Lie bracket becomes a Lie algebra. Every one-dimensional Lie algebra is abelian, by the alternating property of the Lie bracket.\nWhen \"F\" is the real numbers, formula_66 is the Lie algebra of the general linear group formula_67, the group of invertible \"n\" x \"n\" real matrices (or equivalently, matrices with nonzero determinant), where the group operation is matrix multiplication. Likewise, formula_68 is the Lie algebra of the complex Lie group formula_69. The Lie bracket on formula_70 describes the failure of commutativity for matrix multiplication, or equivalently for the composition of linear maps. For any field \"F\", formula_71 can be viewed as the Lie algebra of the algebraic group formula_72 over \"F\".\nDefinitions.\nSubalgebras, ideals and homomorphisms.\nThe Lie bracket is not required to be associative, meaning that formula_73 need not be equal to formula_74. Nonetheless, much of the terminology for associative rings and algebras (and also for groups) has analogs for Lie algebras. A Lie subalgebra is a linear subspace formula_75 which is closed under the Lie bracket. An ideal formula_76 is a linear subspace that satisfies the stronger condition:\nformula_77\nIn the correspondence between Lie groups and Lie algebras, subgroups correspond to Lie subalgebras, and normal subgroups correspond to ideals.\nA Lie algebra homomorphism is a linear map compatible with the respective Lie brackets:\nformula_78\nAn isomorphism of Lie algebras is a bijective homomorphism.\nAs with normal subgroups in groups, ideals in Lie algebras are precisely the kernels of homomorphisms. Given a Lie algebra formula_7 and an ideal formula_80 in it, the \"quotient Lie algebra\" formula_81 is defined, with a surjective homomorphism formula_82 of Lie algebras. The first isomorphism theorem holds for Lie algebras: for any homomorphism formula_83 of Lie algebras, the image of formula_84 is a Lie subalgebra of formula_85 that is isomorphic to formula_86.\nFor the Lie algebra of a Lie group, the Lie bracket is a kind of infinitesimal commutator. As a result, for any Lie algebra, two elements formula_87 are said to \"commute\" if their bracket vanishes: formula_88.\nThe centralizer subalgebra of a subset formula_89 is the set