 Lie algebra.\nInformally speaking, the space of derivations of \"A\" is the Lie algebra of the automorphism group of \"A\". (This is literally true when the automorphism group is a Lie group, for example when \"F\" is the real numbers and \"A\" has finite dimension as a vector space.) For this reason, spaces of derivations are a natural way to construct Lie algebras: they are the \"infinitesimal automorphisms\" of \"A\". Indeed, writing out the condition that\nformula_135\n(where 1 denotes the identity map on \"A\") gives exactly the definition of \"D\" being a derivation.\nExample: the Lie algebra of vector fields. Let \"A\" be the ring formula_136 of smooth functions on a smooth manifold \"X\". Then a derivation of \"A\" over formula_137 is equivalent to a vector field on \"X\". (A vector field \"v\" gives a derivation of the space of smooth functions by differentiating functions in the direction of \"v\".) This makes the space formula_138 of vector fields into a Lie algebra (see Lie bracket of vector fields). Informally speaking, formula_138 is the Lie algebra of the diffeomorphism group of \"X\". So the Lie bracket of vector fields describes the non-commutativity of the diffeomorphism group. An action of a Lie group \"G\" on a manifold \"X\" determines a homomorphism of Lie algebras formula_140. (An example is illustrated below.)\nA Lie algebra can be viewed as a non-associative algebra, and so each Lie algebra formula_7 over a field \"F\" determines its Lie algebra of derivations, formula_142. That is, a derivation of formula_7 is a linear map formula_144 such that\nformula_145.\nThe \"inner derivation\" associated to any formula_146 is the adjoint mapping formula_147 defined by formula_148. (This is a derivation as a consequence of the Jacobi identity.) That gives a homomorphism of Lie algebras, formula_149. The image formula_150 is an ideal in formula_142, and the Lie algebra of \"outer derivations\" is defined as the quotient Lie algebra, formula_152. (This is exactly analogous to the outer automorphism group of a group.) For a semisimple Lie algebra (defined below) over a field of characteristic zero, every derivation is inner. This is related to the theorem that the outer automorphism group of a semisimple Lie group is finite.\nIn contrast, an abelian Lie algebra has many outer derivations. Namely, for a vector space formula_53 with Lie bracket zero, the Lie algebra formula_154 can be identified with formula_62.\nExamples.\nMatrix Lie algebras.\nA matrix group is a Lie group consisting of invertible matrices, formula_156, where the group operation of \"G\" is matrix multiplication. The corresponding Lie algebra formula_1 is the space of matrices which are tangent vectors to \"G\" inside the linear space formula_158: this consists of derivatives of smooth curves in \"G\" at the identity matrix formula_159:\nformula_160\nThe Lie bracket of formula_7 is given by the commutator of matrices, formula_19. Given a Lie algebra formula_163, one can recover the Lie group as the subgroup generated by the matrix exponential of elements of formula_7. (To be precise, this gives the identity component of \"G\", if \"G\" is not connected.) Here the exponential mapping formula_165 is defined by formula_166, which converges for every matrix formula_167.\nThe same comments apply to complex Lie subgroups of formula_168 and the complex matrix exponential, formula_169 (defined by the same formula).\nHere are some matrix Lie groups and their Lie algebras.\nThe complex orthogonal group formula_186, its identity component formula_187, and the Lie algebra formula_188 are given by the same formulas applied to \"n\" x \"n\" complex matrices. Equivalently, formula_186 is the subgroup of formula_69 that preserves the standard symmetric bilinear form on formula_191.\nTwo dimensions.\nSome Lie algebras of low dimension are described here. See the classification of low-dimensional real Lie algebras for further examples.\nThe affine group \"G\" can b